      =\n|established = 28 December 1914\n|first_award = 1 January 1915 to 98 officers and warrant officers.<ref name=Warrant>{{London Gazette |issue=29024 |date=29 December 1914 |pages=7\u20139  |supp=y}}</ref>\n|last_award  =\n|total       = Including further awards:<ref name=Abbott220/><br>[[George V]]: c. 43,500<br />[[George VI]]: over 11,500<br />[[Elizabeth II]]: c. 750\n|posthumous  =\n|recipients  = Over 52,000\n|individual  =\n|precedence_label=Order of Wear\n|higher      = [[Conspicuous Gallantry Cross]]<ref name=JSP761>{{cite web |title=JSP 761 Honours and Awards in the Armed Forces |url=http://ndm-pr.webs.com/jsp761%5B1%5D.pdf |page=12A\u20131 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n|same        =\n|lower       = [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]]<ref name=JSP761/>\n|related= [[Military Medal]]\n|image2      = [[File:Military cross BAR.svg|center|100px]]<br>[[File:Military cross w bar BAR.svg|center|100px]]<br>[[File:Military cross w 2bars BAR.svg|center|100px]]Military Cross ribbon:<br>without bar, and with one and two bars\n|caption2    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Military Cross''' ('''MC''') is the third-level (second-level pre-1993) [[military decoration]] awarded to officers and (since 1993) other ranks of the [[British Armed Forces]], and formerly awarded to officers of other [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries.\n\nThe MC is granted in recognition of \"an act or acts of exemplary gallantry during active operations against the enemy on land\" to all members of the British Armed Forces of any rank.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56693 |supp=y|page=11146|date=17 October 2002}}</ref> In 1979, the Queen approved a proposal that a number of awards, including the Military Cross, could be recommended posthumously.<ref>Abbott & Tamplin, ''British Gallantry Awards'', 2nd edition. p. xx.</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe award was created on 28 December 1914 for [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned officers]] of the substantive rank of [[Captain (land)|captain]] or below and for [[warrant officer]]s. The first 98 awards were gazetted on 1 January 1915, to 71 officers, and 27 warrant officers. Although posthumous recommendations for the Military Cross wer unavailable until 1979, the first awards included seven posthumous awards, with the word 'deceased' after the name of the recipient, from recommendations that had been raised before the recipients died of wounds or lost their lives from other causes.<ref name=Warrant/>\n\nAwards are announced in ''The London Gazette'', apart from most honorary awards to allied forces in keeping with the usual practice not to gazette awards to foreigners.<ref name=Abbott219>Abbott & Tamplin, ''British Gallantry Awards'', 2nd edition. p. 219.</ref>\n\nFrom August 1916, recipients of the Cross were entitled to use the [[post-nominal letters]] MC,<ref>Revised Royal Warrant, clause 8. {{London Gazette|issue=29725|supp=y|page=8472|date=25 August 1916}}</ref> and [[Medal bar|bars]] could be awarded for further acts of gallantry meriting the award,<ref>Revisied Royal Warrant, clause 5. {{London Gazette|issue=29725|supp=y|page=8471|date=25 August 1916}}</ref> with a silver rosette worn on the ribbon when worn alone to denote the award of each bar.\n\nFrom September 1916, members of the [[63rd (Royal Naval) Division|Royal Naval Division]], who served alongside the Army on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]], were made eligible for military decorations, including the Military Cross, for the war's duration.<ref name=Abbott217>Abbott & Tamplin, British Gallantry Awards, 2nd edition. page 217.</ref> Naval officers serving with the division received 140 MCs and eight second award bars.<ref name=Abbott220/>\n\nIn June 1917, eligibility was extended to temporary [[major]]s, not above the substantive rank of captain.<ref>\"The Military Cross, Royal Warrant of 25th June, 1917, amending the Third Clause of The Military Cross Warrant of 23rd August, 1916\", War Office 3 July 1917 {{London Gazette|issue=30161|page=6550|date=3 July 1917}}</ref> Substantive majors were made eligible in 1953.<ref name=Abbott218>Abbott & Tamplin, ''British Gallantry Awards'', 2nd edition. page 218.</ref>\n\nIn 1931, the award was extended to equivalent ranks in the [[Royal Air Force]] for actions on the ground.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33700|page=1890|date=20 March 1931}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Second World War, most [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries created their own honours system and no longer recommended British awards. The last Military Cross awards for the Canadian Army were for Korea. The last four Australian Army Military Cross awards were promulgated in ''The London Gazette'' on 1 September 1972 for Vietnam as was the last New Zealand Army Military Cross award, which was promulgated on 25 September 1970. [[Orders, decorations, and medals of Canada|Canada]], [[Australian Honours System|Australia]] and [[New Zealand Royal Honours System|New Zealand]] have now created their own gallantry awards under their own honours systems.\n\nSince the 1993 review of the honours system, as part of the drive to remove distinctions of rank in awards for bravery, the [[Military Medal]], formerly the third-level decoration for [[Other ranks (UK)|other ranks]], has been discontinued. The MC now serves as the third-level award for all ranks of the British Armed Forces for gallantry on land, not to the standard required to receive the [[Victoria Cross]] or the [[Conspicuous Gallantry Cross]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceFor/Veterans/Medals/MilitaryCrossmc.htm |title=Military Cross (MC) |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |accessdate=30 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe Military Cross has the following design:<ref name=Mussell>John Mussell, Medal Yearbook 2015. page 87.</ref>\n* 46&nbsp;mm maximum height, 44&nbsp;mm maximum width.\n* Ornamental silver cross with straight arms terminating in broad finials, suspended from a plain suspension bar.\n* Obverse decorated with [[Imperial State Crown|imperial crowns]], with the [[Royal Cypher]] in centre.\n* Reverse is plain. From 1938 until 1957 the year of award was engraved on lower limb of cross,<ref name=Duckers>Peter Duckers, British Gallantry Awards 1855 \u2013 2000. pp 26-27.</ref> and since 1984 it has been awarded named to the recipient.<ref name=Mussell/>\n* The ribbon width is 32&nbsp;mm and consists of three equal vertical [[moire (fabric)|moire]] stripes of white, purple, and white.\n* Ribbon bar denoting a further award is plain silver, with a crown in the centre.\n\n== Recipients ==\n=== Numbers awarded ===\nSince 1914 over 52,000 Military Crosses and 3,717 bars have been awarded.<ref name=Abbott220/> The dates below reflect the relevant ''London Gazette'' entries:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n! Period || ||align=center| Medals|| 1st bar || 2nd bar|| 3rd bar|| || Honorary<br>MCs|| Honorary<br>MC bars\n|-\n|align=center| World War I||align=center| 1914\u201320 ||align=center| 37,104 ||align=center| 2,984 ||align=center| 169 ||align=center| 4 || ||align=center| 2,909<ref>The World War I records are incomplete, see page 220, British Gallantry Awards, (2nd ed), Abbott & Tamplin.</ref> ||align=center| \u2013\n|-\n|align=center| Inter\u2013War || align=center| 1920\u201339 ||align=center| 349 ||align=center| 31 ||align=center| \u2013  ||align=center| \u2013 || ||align=center| \u2013 ||align=center| \u2013\n|-\n|align=center| World War II ||align=center| 1939\u201346 ||align=center| 10,386||align=center| 482 ||align=center| 24 ||align=center| \u2013 || ||align=center| 438||align=center| 3\n|-\n|align=center| Post\u2013War ||align=center| 1947\u201379||align=center|643||align=center| 20 ||align=center| \u2013 ||align=center| \u2013 || ||align=center| \u2013 ||align=center| \u2013\n|-\n|align=center| '''Total''' ||align=center| '''1914\u201379''' ||align=center| '''48,482''' ||align=center| '''3,517''' ||align=center| '''193''' ||align=center| '''4''' || ||align=center|''' 3,347'''||align=center|'''3'''\n|}\n\nIn addition, approximately 375 MCs have been awarded since 1979, including awards for [[The Troubles|Northern Ireland]], the [[Falklands War|Falklands]] and the wars in the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf]], [[Iraq War|Iraq]] and [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]].<ref>Post 1979 MCs include 16 for the [[Falklands War|Falklands]] ([https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/49134/supplement/12831 ''London Gazette Supplement'', 8 October 1982]); 11 for [[Gulf War]] ([https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/52588/supplement/1 ''London Gazette Supplement'', 29 June 1991]); 84 for [[List of British gallantry awards for the Iraq War#Military Cross|Iraq]] and 215+1 bar for [[List of British gallantry awards for the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)#Military Cross|Afghanistan]], plus awards for [[The Troubles|Northern Ireland]] and smaller conflicts.</ref>\n\nThe above table includes awards to the Dominions:<br>In all, 3,727 Military Crosses have been awarded to those serving with Canadian forces, including 324 first bars and 18 second bars.<ref>[http://www.veterans.gc.ca/eng/remembrance/medals-decorations/details/45 Veterans Affairs Canada \u2013 Military Cross] (Retrieved 7 November 2018)</ref><br>A total of 2,930 were awarded to Australians, in addition to 188 first bars and four second bars. Of these, 2,403 MCs, 170 first Bars and four second Bars were for World War I.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060623051652/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/awards/imperial.cfm#mc |title=Imperial Awards |work=It's an Honour |publisher=[[Australian Government]] |accessdate=7 November 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060623051652/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/awards/imperial.cfm#mc |archivedate=23 June 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><br>Over 500 MCs were awarded to New Zealanders during World War I and over 250 in World War II. The most recent awards were for service in Vietnam.<ref>[http://medals.nzdf.mil.nz/category/i/i9.html New Zealand Defence Force: British Commonwealth Gallantry Awards - The Military Cross] (Retrieved 7 November 2018)</ref>\n\nThe honorary MC awards were made to servicemen from fifteen Allied countries in World War I, and nine in World War II.<ref name=Abbott220/>\n\n=== Notable awards ===\n{{see also category|Recipients of the Military Cross}}\n<!--Please do NOT add recipients, just because they have received an MC - there are over 48,000 recipients.  This section is just for notable \"firsts\" -->\n\n[[File:Jacka-MC&bar.jpg|thumb|x220px|[[Albert Jacka]]'s MC<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29824|supp=y|page=11074|date=14 November 1916}}</ref> and bar<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30135|supp=y|page=5983|date=15 June 1917}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Military Cross awarded 1915 to 2nd Lt. E. W. Fane de Salis (1894-1980).jpg|thumb|x220px|MC awarded to 2nd Lt. E. W. Fane de Salis (1894-1980)<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30111|supp=y|page=5478|date=1 June 1917}}</ref>]]\n* During World War I, Acting Captain [[Francis Wallington]] of the [[Royal Field Artillery]] was the first person to be awarded the MC and three bars when he was invested with his third bar on 10 July 1918 (gazetted 13 September 1918: he had obtained the first three awards as a second lieutenant).<ref name=\"addington\">Scott Addington; [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Uw98jVk5pkoC&pg=PA343&lpg=PA352 ''For Conspicuous Gallantry... Winners of the Military Cross and Bar during the Great War. Volume 1 \u2013 Two Bars & Three Bars''], Troubador Publishing Ltd, 2006, pp.343\u2013352.</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30901 |supp=y |page=10877 |date=13 September 1918 }} ''(Wallington)''</ref> Three other officers were subsequently awarded a third bar, [[Percy Bentley (soldier)|Percy Bentley]], [[Humphrey Arthur Gilkes]] and [[Charles Gordon Timms]], all of whose awards appeared in a supplement to the ''London Gazette'' on 31 January 1919.<ref name=\"addington\"/><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31158 |supp=y |page=1617 |date=31 January 1919 }} ''(Bentley, Gilkes & Timms)''</ref>\n* For their key roles during World War I, the cities of [[Verdun]] and [[Ypres]] were awarded the Military Cross, in September 1916 and February 1920 respectively.<ref name=Abbott220>Abbott & Tamplin, British Gallantry Awards, 2nd edition. pp 220-222.</ref> In May 1920, [[John French, 1st Earl of Ypres|Field Marshal French]] presented the decoration to Ypres in a special ceremony in the city.<ref>[https://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205178222 Award of the Military Cross to the City of Ypres, Imperial War Museum]</ref>\n* During World War II Captain [[Sam Manekshaw]], [[Indian Army]] (who eventually rose to the rank of Field Marshal), was leading a counter-offensive operation against the invading Japanese Army in Burma. During the course of the offensive, he was hit by a burst of machine-gun fire and severely wounded in the stomach.  Major General [[David Tennent Cowan|D.T. Cowan]] spotted Manekshaw holding on to life and was aware of his valour in face of stiff resistance from the Japanese. Fearing the worst, Major General Cowan quickly pinned his own Military Cross ribbon on to Manekshaw saying, \"A dead person cannot be awarded a Military Cross.\"<ref>Compton McKenzie (1951), ''Eastern Epic'', Chatto & Windus, London, pp. 440\u20131.</ref>\n* The first posthumous Military Cross was that awarded to Captain [[Herbert Westmacott]], [[Grenadier Guards]] for gallantry in Northern Ireland during the period 1 February 1980 to 30 April 1980.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=48346 |supp=y |page=14608 |date=20 October 1980}} ''(Westmacott)''</ref>\n* The first woman to be awarded the Military Cross was Private [[Michelle Norris]] of the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]], while attached to The [[Princess of Wales's Royal Regiment]] for her actions in Iraq on 11 June 2006. Norris was awarded her medal personally by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] on 21 March 2007.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58183 |supp=y |page=17359 |date=15 December 2006 }} ''(Norris)''</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = David | last = Wilkes | title = Heroine teenage soldier to be decorated for bravery | url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=399779&in_page_id=1770 |work=Daily Mail |location=UK |publisher = [[Associated Newspapers]] |issn = 0307-7578 |date = 10 August 2006 |accessdate =22 March 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news | first = Lee | last = Glendinning | title = Historic award for female private | url = https://www.theguardian.com/military/story/0,,2039749,00.html |work=The Guardian |location=UK | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]] | issn = 0261-3077 | page = 8 | date = 22 March 2007 | accessdate =22 March 2007}}</ref>\n* Able Seaman [[Kate Nesbitt]], second woman, first in the Royal Navy, for acts in Afghanistan in March 2009 as a Medical Assistant attached to 1 RIFLES, 3 Commando Brigade.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59182 |date=11 September 2009 |page=15640 |supp=y }} ''(Nesbitt)''</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=First female Royal Navy medic awarded Military Cross |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/defence/6670207/First-female-Royal-Navy-medic-awarded-Military-Cross.html|newspaper=Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group|location=London|date=27 November 2009|accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n* Sergeant [[Michael Lockett]] MC was the first holder of the MC to be [[killed in action]] since [[World War II]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=58633|supp=y|page=3613|date=7 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Norton-Taylor|first=Richard|title=Soldier Killed in Afghanistan Has Been Awarded Military Cross|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/sep/22/dead-soldier-military-cross|accessdate=17 November 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=22 September 2009}}</ref>\n<!--Please do NOT add recipients, just because they have received an MC - there are over 48,000 recipients.  This section is just for notable \"firsts\" -->\n\n== See also ==\n* [[:Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n* [[British and Commonwealth orders and decorations]]\n* [[List of British gallantry awards for the Iraq War]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Abbott, Peter and Tamplin, John. ''British Gallantry Awards'', 2nd edition (1981). Nimrod Dix and Co., London. {{ISBN|9780902633742}}.\n* Duckers, Peter. ''British Gallantry Awards 1855\u20132000'' (2011). Shire Publications, Risborough, Buckinghamshire. {{ISBN|9780747805168}}.\n* Mussell, J. (ed.). ''Medals Yearbook 2015'' (2014). Token Publishing, Honiton, Devon. {{ISBN| 9781908828163}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/29024/supplement/7 Original Royal Warrant for the MC] ''Supplement to London Gazette'', 1 January 1915\n* [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/56693/supplement/11146 Current Royal Warrant for the MC] ''Supplement to London Gazette'', 17 September 2002\n* [http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?show=simple Database of Australian Awardees] at the Australian Government Honours [https://web.archive.org/web/20190515213714/http://itsanhonour.gov.au/ website]\n* [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/wo373.asp Search recommendations for the Military Cross] The UK National Archives\n* {{cite web|url= http://www.kingsownmuseum.com/medalsaa.htm|title= Military Cross|work= The King's Own Royal Regiment Museum, Lancaster}}\n* [http://www.northeastmedals.co.uk/britishguide/military_cross/mc.htm Notes on numbers awarded] North East Medals\n\n{{Decorations of the United Kingdom}}\n{{Former Australian Honours}}\n{{South African military decorations and medals}}\n\n[[Category:Courage awards]]\n[[Category:Military awards and decorations of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sp", "url_page": 