{"title_page": "Always Becoming", "text_new": "{{advert|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox Sculpture\n | image  = [[Image:Always Becoming Facing West.JPG|200px]]\n | title  = Always Becoming\n | artist = [[Nora Naranjo-Morse]]\n | year   = 2007\n | type   = Dirt, sand, straw, clay, <br />stone, black locust wood, <br />bamboo, grass, and yam vines.\n | city   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n | museum = <br /> [[National Museum of the American Indian]]\n}}\n\n'''''Always Becoming''''' is an artwork created in 2007 by [[Nora Naranjo-Morse]] (born 1953), a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] [[Pottery|Potter]] and [[poet]]. She currently resides in [[Espa\u00f1ola, New Mexico|Espa\u00f1ola]], [[New Mexico]], just north of [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]] and is a member of the [[Santa Clara Pueblo]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe sculpture consists of five separate sculptures, that make up a family.\n\nGrounded in figures from [[Santa Clara Pueblo]] oral tradition the sculptures are named:\n* Father\n* Mother\n* Little one\n* Moon Woman\n* Mountain Bird\n\nThe sculptures were built in-situ over the summer of 2007, Nora Naranjo-Morse worked with her niece Athena Swentzell Steen and her husband Bill Steen who are experts at building structures with natural material, and the family of Don Juan Morales ([[Tepehuan]]) from the Mexican state of  [[Durango]], as well as many volunteers including museum staff and visitors.\n\n{{quote|Being strangers at the beginning of this journey, we came from distant places with the intent to build sculptures, and in the process built a family as well.|Nora Naranajo-Morse, 2007 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmai.si.edu/alwaysbecoming/AlwaysBecoming.html|title=NMAI: NORA NARANJO-MORSE-ALWAYS BECOMING MALL SCULPTURE PROJECT|website=www.nmai.si.edu|access-date=2017-01-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106005120/http://nmai.si.edu/alwaysbecoming/AlwaysBecoming.html|archive-date=2017-01-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n\n==Materials==\n\nThe Sculptures are made entirely of natural materials: dirt, sand, straw, clay, stone, black locust wood, bamboo, grass, and yam vines. These natural elements were selected to take on a life of their own and thus affect the sculptures over time. In this way the materials ensure the forms are 'always becoming'.\n\n==Dimensions==\n\nThe five sculptures range in size from seven and a half to sixteen feet tall.\n\n==History and Location==\n\nOn May 24, 2006, the [[National Museum of the American Indian]] announced that Naranjo-Morse had won its outdoor sculpture design competition. \"Always Becoming\" was selected unanimously from more than 55 entries submitted by Native artists from throughout the Western Hemisphere.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmai.si.edu/press/releases/2006-05-24_outdoor_sculpture_release_final_1.pdf|title=Press {{!}} National Museum of the American Indian|website=www.nmai.si.edu|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\nDuring the summer of 2007, on the grounds of the National Museum of the American Indian, [[Washington, DC]], Naranjo-Morse built a family of clay sculptures. The commissioned work is located on the 'Native landscape' at the museum's south entrance on Maryland Avenue S.W. near 4th Street and Independence Avenue S.W., Washington, D.C.\n\nA public dedication, officially opening these public works of art, took place on September 1, 2007.\n\nThe sculptures are intended to disintegrate over time, and the lives of sculptures from the initial idea through the continued process of [[stewardship]] are being documented by Filmmaker Dax Thomas ([[Laguna Pueblo|Laguna]]/[[Acoma Pueblo|Acoma]]). As the sculptures disintegrate the films of their life will form a more permanent record of their existence and are therefore an essential part of the artistic process, and the work of art itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/quatica|title=quatica|website=Vimeo|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Native culture and the environment served as the inspiration for the sculpture design.  'Always Becoming' will reflect themes of growth and adaptation and represent indigenous peoples' unique relationship to the environment, ...\n\nThe sculpture's metaphor of home and family not only conveys a universal theme to all peoples, but also enhances the visitors' experience that they have entered a Native place when they {{sic|step foot}} on the museum grounds.|Nora Naranajo-Morse, 2007 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.caneloproject.com/pages/currrent%20projects/smithsonian.html|title=always becoming|website=www.caneloproject.com|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref> }}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080927043059/http://www.nmai.si.edu/alwaysbecoming/AlwaysBecoming.html ''Always Becoming'' Official Website] at the [[National Museum of the American Indian]]\n*[http://alwaysbecomingfilm.blogspot.com/ ''Always Becoming'' blog]\n* [http://www.nmai.si.edu/press/releases/2006-05-24_outdoor_sculpture_release_final_1.pdf NMAI Announcement of ''Always Becoming'' as the winner of the Outdoor sculpture Design Competition]\n* [http://www.indianz.com/board/topic.asp?ARCHIVE=true&TOPIC_ID=21369 indianz.com Announcement of the NMAI\u2019s outdoor Sculpture Design Competition Winner]\n* [http://www.caneloproject.com/pages/currrent%20projects/smithsonian.html Canelo Project]\n* [http://www.nativenetworks.si.edu/Eng/orange/always_becoming.htm Smithsonian Institution \u2018Native Networks\u2019]\n* [http://www.nativenetworks.si.edu/Eng/rose/thomas_d.htm Native Networks entry for Dax Thomas (Laguna/Acoma) the film maker making the film of the project]\n* [http://www.nativenetworks.si.edu/Eng/rose/naranjo_morse_n.htm Nora Naranjo-Morse entry on Native Networks]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071015163939/http://tanasijournal.com/main/index.php?option=com_content Tanasi Journal]\n* [http://www.voanews.com/specialenglish/archive/2007-09/2007-09-18-voa1.cfm Voice of America News: \"Five New Sculptures Welcome Visitors to American Indian Museum\"]\n* [http://www.follow.xt.pl/?s=always+becoming Follow.xt.pl: Blog entries about the videos by Dax Thomas]\n* [http://www.gosmithsonian.com/museums/national-museum-of-the-american-indian/nmaidc-exhibits.html Go Smithsonian]\n* [http://homesweetfarm.blogspot.com/2007/10/always-becoming.html Home Sweet Farm: Cultivating Stewardship, Growing Righteous Food (blog): ''Always Becoming'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080927122739/http://www.swaia.org/board.php Southwestern Association for Indian Arts: Board of Directors \u2018Nora Naranjo-Morse\u2019 Biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080705032004/http://www.smithsonianmag.com/arts-culture/200711-sculpting.html ''Smithsonian Magazine'' Article: Sculpting Her Vision. By Nicole Wroten 'Smithsonian.com' October 31, 2007]\n* [http://digyourhandsinthedirt.blogspot.com/2008/02/always-becoming.html Dig your Hands in the Dirt: Making Art of the Earth Together (Blog)] Friday, February 8, 2008 ''Always Becoming'' \u2013 Story and photos (except where noted) by Bill Steen\n\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{coord|38|53|17|N|77|0|59|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Always Becoming}}\n[[Category:American contemporary art]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2007 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of the Smithsonian Institution]]\n[[Category:Contemporary works of art]]\n[[Category:Digital art]]\n[[Category:Native Americans in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Pueblo art]]\n[[Category:Preservation (library and archival science)]]\n[[Category:Southwest Federal Center]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox Sculpture\n | image  = [[Image:Always Becoming Facing West.JPG|200px]]\n | title  = Always Becoming\n | artist = [[Nora Naranjo-Morse]]\n | year   = 2007\n | type   = Dirt, sand, straw, clay, <br />stone, black locust wood, <br />bamboo, grass, and yam vines.\n | city   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n | museum = <br /> [[National Museum of the American Indian]]\n}}\n\n'''''Always Becoming''''' is an artwork created in 2007 by [[Nora Naranjo-Morse]] (born 1953), a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] [[Pottery|Potter]] and [[poet]]. She currently resides in [[Espa\u00f1ola, New Mexico|Espa\u00f1ola]], [[New Mexico]], just north of [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]] and is a member of the [[Santa Clara Pueblo]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe sculpture consists of five separate sculptures, that make up a family.\n\nGrounded in figures from [[Santa Clara Pueblo]] oral tradition the sculptures are named:\n* Father\n* Mother\n* Little one\n* Moon Woman\n* Mountain Bird\n\nThe sculptures were built in-situ over the summer of 2007, Nora Naranjo-Morse worked with her niece Athena Swentzell Steen and her husband Bill Steen who are experts at building structures with natural material, and the family of Don Juan Morales ([[Tepehuan]]) from the Mexican state of  [[Durango]], as well as many volunteers including museum staff and visitors.\n\n{{quote|Being strangers at the beginning of this journey, we came from distant places with the intent to build sculptures, and in the process built a family as well.|Nora Naranajo-Morse, 2007 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmai.si.edu/alwaysbecoming/AlwaysBecoming.html|title=NMAI: NORA NARANJO-MORSE-ALWAYS BECOMING MALL SCULPTURE PROJECT|website=www.nmai.si.edu|access-date=2017-01-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106005120/http://nmai.si.edu/alwaysbecoming/AlwaysBecoming.html|archive-date=2017-01-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n\n==Materials==\n\nThe Sculptures are made entirely of natural materials: dirt, sand, straw, clay, stone, black locust wood, bamboo, grass, and yam vines. These natural elements were selected to take on a life of their own and thus affect the sculptures over time. In this way the materials ensure the forms are 'always becoming'.\n\n==Dimensions==\n\nThe five sculptures range in size from seven and a half to sixteen feet tall.\n\n==History and Location==\n\nOn May 24, 2006, the [[National Museum of the American Indian]] announced that Naranjo-Morse had won its outdoor sculpture design competition. \"Always Becoming\" was selected unanimously from more than 55 entries submitted by Native artists from throughout the Western Hemisphere.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmai.si.edu/press/releases/2006-05-24_outdoor_sculpture_release_final_1.pdf|title=Press {{!}} National Museum of the American Indian|website=www.nmai.si.edu|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\nDuring the summer of 2007, on the grounds of the National Museum of the American Indian, [[Washington, DC]], Naranjo-Morse built a family of clay sculptures. The commissioned work is located on the 'Native landscape' at the museum's south entrance on Maryland Avenue S.W. near 4th Street and Independence Avenue S.W., Washington, D.C.\n\nA public dedication, officially opening these public works of art, took place on September 1, 2007.\n\nThe sculptures are intended to disintegrate over time, and the lives of sculptures from the initial idea through the continued process of [[stewardship]] are being documented by Filmmaker Dax Thomas ([[Laguna Pueblo|Laguna]]/[[Acoma Pueblo|Acoma]]). As the sculptures disintegrate the films of their life will form a more permanent record of their existence and are therefore an essential part of the artistic process, and the work of art itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/quatica|title=quatica|website=Vimeo|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Native culture and the environment served as the inspiration for the sculpture design.  'Always Becoming' will reflect themes of growth and adaptation and represent indigenous peoples' unique relationship to the environment, ...\n\nThe sculpture's metaphor of home and family not only conveys a universal theme to all peoples, but also enhances the visitors' experience that they have entered a Native place when they {{sic|step foot}} on the museum grounds.|Nora Naranajo-Morse, 2007 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.caneloproject.com/pages/currrent%20projects/smithsonian.html|title=always becoming|website=www.caneloproject.com|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref> }}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080927043059/http://www.nmai.si.edu/alwaysbecoming/AlwaysBecoming.html ''Always Becoming'' Official Website] at the [[National Museum of the American Indian]]\n*[http://alwaysbecomingfilm.blogspot.com/ ''Always Becoming'' blog]\n* [http://www.nmai.si.edu/press/releases/2006-05-24_outdoor_sculpture_release_final_1.pdf NMAI Announcement of ''Always Becoming'' as the winner of the Outdoor sculpture Design Competition]\n* [http://www.indianz.com/board/topic.asp?ARCHIVE=true&TOPIC_ID=21369 indianz.com Announcement of the NMAI\u2019s outdoor Sculpture Design Competition Winner]\n* [http://www.caneloproject.com/pages/currrent%20projects/smithsonian.html Canelo Project]\n* [http://www.nativenetworks.si.edu/Eng/orange/always_becoming.htm Smithsonian Institution \u2018Native Networks\u2019]\n* [http://www.nativenetworks.si.edu/Eng/rose/thomas_d.htm Native Networks entry for Dax Thomas (Laguna/Acoma) the film maker making the film of the project]\n* [http://www.nativenetworks.si.edu/Eng/rose/naranjo_morse_n.htm Nora Naranjo-Morse entry on Native Networks]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071015163939/http://tanasijournal.com/main/index.php?option=com_content Tanasi Journal]\n* [http://www.voanews.com/specialenglish/archive/2007-09/2007-09-18-voa1.cfm Voice of America News: \"Five New Sculptures Welcome Visitors to American Indian Museum\"]\n* [http://www.follow.xt.pl/?s=always+becoming Follow.xt.pl: Blog entries about the videos by Dax Thomas]\n* [http://www.gosmithsonian.com/museums/national-museum-of